excerpt: New Zealand's principal museum tracking native and colonial culture as well as natural history.
detail_description: The Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa is a must-visit attraction in Wellington, offering free admission to its extensive collection. This national museum showcases natural history, cultural exhibits, and fine arts across six levels. Visitors can explore interactive displays and national treasures, including indigenous Maori exhibitions and the national art collection. Notable attractions include a colossal squid specimen and an earthquake simulator.
name: Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa
address: 55 Cable Street, Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Botanic garden of 61-acres, planted in 1868 with native bush, tropical greenhouse and seasonal beds.
detail_description: Wellington Botanic Garden, established in 1868, spans 61 acres and offers a variety of attractions for visitors. It features native bush, a tropical greenhouse, seasonal beds, and colorful floral displays. The garden provides numerous walking routes suitable for families or solo explorers seeking a peaceful retreat from the city.
name: Wellington Botanic Garden
address: 101 Glenmore Street, Kelburn, Wellington 6012, New Zealand

excerpt: Opened in 1902, the country's only running cablecar offers panoramic city views & a history museum.
detail_description: The Wellington Cable Car, the only operating funicular in New Zealand, has been in service since 1902. It provides stunning panoramic views of the city and offers a visit to the historic museum. A must-visit attraction is Te Papa, an interactive national museum showcasing the stories of Aotearoa New Zealand. After riding the iconic cable car, visitors can enjoy breathtaking city views while indulging in ice cream at the top.
name: Wellington Cable Car
address: 280 Lambton Quay, Wellington Central, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Cool museum in a historic building with various unique exhibits showcasing the region's history.
detail_description: Wellington Museum is a captivating museum housed in a preserved historic building, offering various unique exhibits that showcase the region's history. The state-of-the-art multimedia displays bring the city's maritime history and evolution to life. One of its notable exhibits focuses on the 1968 Wahine disaster, serving as a poignant reminder of Wellington's connection to the sea and the power of nature.
name: Wellington Museum
address: 3 Jervois Quay, Wellington Central, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Mount Victoria is a suburb of central Wellington, New Zealand, named after the 196 metres hill Mount Victoria to the east. Mount Victoria's residential area is on its north-western slopes. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Mount Victoria is a suburb in central Wellington, New Zealand, named after the 196-meter hill to the east. The residential area is situated on its north-western slopes. It offers stunning panoramic views of Wellington city, the harbor, and Cook Strait. There are various tracks for hiking and mountain biking that lead up and around Mount Vic, with a lookout track leading to the top for breathtaking views of the entire city.
name: Mount Victoria
address: Wellington, New Zealand

excerpt: The country's first zoo offers animal activities & programs, plus themed playgrounds & picnic areas.
detail_description: Wellington Zoo, the country's first zoo, is a popular attraction offering animal activities and programs for visitors of all ages. It is located in the green belt of Wellington, New Zealand and was established by former Prime Minister Richard Seddon after being gifted with a cub. The zoo features a diverse range of wildlife from around the world, making it an exciting destination for animal lovers.
name: Wellington Zoo
address: 200 Daniell Street, Newtown, Wellington 6021, New Zealand

excerpt: Astronomy & space museum featuring planetarium shows, interactive exhibits & a giant telescope.
detail_description: Space Place at Carter Observatory is a must-visit astronomy and space museum in Wellington, New Zealand. It features planetarium shows, interactive exhibits, and a giant telescope for an immersive stargazing experience. Visitors can explore the stories of New Zealand skies through multimedia exhibits and observe the southern skies through telescopes on clear nights. The museum offers valuable insights into celestial bodies, including planets, stars, constellations, and galaxies while highlighting New Zealand's role in space exploration.
name: Space Place at Carter Observatory
address: 40 Salamanca Road, Kelburn, Wellington 6012, New Zealand

excerpt: Wildlife sanctuary with native species, including rare birds, lizards, frogs, plants & trees.
detail_description: Zealandia Te Māra a Tāne is an extraordinary wildlife sanctuary located just a short drive from Wellington's bustling city center. This eco-park spans 225 hectares of lush, regenerating forest and serves as a haven for native species, including rare birds, lizards, frogs, and unique plant life.
name: Zealandia Te Māra a Tāne
address: 53 Waiapu Road, Karori, Wellington 6012, New Zealand

excerpt: Vibrant gallery with contemporary works by New Zealand & international artists, plus various events.
detail_description: City Gallery Wellington is a vibrant and spacious art space located in a historic building that was once the city library. It showcases contemporary works by both local and international artists, with a changing program of temporary exhibitions throughout the year. The gallery features various forms of modern visual arts, including painting, photography, sculpture, multimedia work, and art installations. In addition to the art displays, visitors can also enjoy talks, performances, and events at this leading contemporary art hub in New Zealand.
name: City Gallery Wellington
address: Te Ngākau Civic Square, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Cuba Street is a vibrant and eclectic area in Wellington, New Zealand. It's known for its bohemian atmosphere, lined with colorful buildings, quirky shops, and trendy cafes. The street is a hub of creativity and culture, with street performers adding to the lively ambiance. Visitors can explore an array of unique boutiques selling everything from vintage clothing to handmade crafts. The dining scene on Cuba Street is diverse, offering a wide range of international cuisines as well as local favorites.
name: Cuba Street
address: Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Matiu/Somes Island, nestled in Wellington Harbour, is a serene escape for nature enthusiasts and history buffs alike. This island, owned by the local Maori and managed by the Department of Conservation, has a rich past as an internment camp, military defense post, and quarantine station. Today, it stands as a meticulously preserved nature reserve where visitors can embark on scenic walks and observe native wildlife.
name: Matiu / Somes Island
address: Wellington Region 5012, New Zealand

excerpt: Tranquil picnic area featuring panoramic vistas of the city, boats, airplanes & sunsets.
detail_description: Mount Victoria Lookout is a must-visit spot in Wellington, offering a tranquil picnic area with breathtaking panoramic views of the city, harbor, and surrounding landscapes. Rising over 640 feet above sea level, this lookout can be reached by driving or hiking and promises an awe-inspiring vista that captures the essence of Wellington. The gentle half-hour walk from the city center to the grassy glade at the summit makes it easily accessible for visitors.
name: Mount Victoria Lookout
address: Lookout Road, Hataitai, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Exhibits of props for "Lord of the Rings" & other films, plus a documentary & studio souvenirs.
detail_description: The Weta Cave in Wellington is a must-visit for fans of 'Lord of the Rings' and 'The Hobbit' trilogies. It's the tourist-facing part of Weta Workshop and Studios, where props, special effects, and movie art have been created for various films. Visitors can explore exhibits featuring props from these blockbuster movies, as well as behind-the-scenes tours showcasing the creation of special effects for films like 'Avatar,' 'District 9,' and more.
name: Weta Cave
address: 1 Weka Street, Miramar, Wellington 6022, New Zealand

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Wellington, Wētā Workshop stands as a beacon of creativity and innovation in the realm of special effects and prop creation. Renowned for its groundbreaking work on iconic films like The Lord of the Rings Trilogy, Avatar, and King Kong, this studio has captivated audiences with its stunning visual storytelling. While you can't tour the live workshop due to confidentiality surrounding new projects, a visit to the adjacent Wētā Cave offers an exciting glimpse into their world.
name: Weta Workshop
address: 21 Camperdown Road, Miramar, Wellington 6022, New Zealand

excerpt: Popular harborside trail with artisan shops, waterside dining & kids' playgrounds, plus statues.
detail_description: The Wellington Waterfront Walk is a popular harborside trail that offers a great short walk along the coastline, with access to some of Wellington's best beaches and fantastic views across the harbor. The promenade runs from Frank Kitts Park to Te Papa museum, Waitangi Park, and Oriental Bay. Once a bustling harbor and busy port, it now boasts stunning skyline views and separates the central city from the sea.
name: Wellington Waterfront Walk
address: Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Oriental Bay is a bay and suburb of Wellington, the capital city of New Zealand. Known for being both a popular beach and an opulent centre of affluence in the city, it is located close to the central business district on Wellington Harbour. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Oriental Bay, a suburb of Wellington, New Zealand, is situated on the Wellington Harbour and is known for its popular beach and affluent community. It is the closest seaside area to the city center and offers a prime location for swimming, cycling, and waterfront dining during the summer months. Originally named Duppa after its first resident, it was later renamed Oriental Bay after the ship that brought him to Wellington.
name: Oriental Bay
address: Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Wellington, the capital of New Zealand, sits near the North Island’s southernmost point on the Cook Strait. A compact city, it encompasses a waterfront promenade, sandy beaches, a working harbour and colourful timber houses on surrounding hills. From Lambton Quay, the iconic red Wellington Cable Car heads to the Wellington Botanic Gardens. Strong winds through the Cook Strait give it the nickname "Windy Wellington."
detail_description: Wellington, the capital of New Zealand, is a vibrant city located near the southernmost point of the North Island. Known for its picturesque waterfront, sandy beaches, and colorful timber houses dotting the hillsides, Wellington offers a unique blend of natural beauty and urban charm. The iconic red Wellington Cable Car provides access to the Wellington Botanic Gardens from Lambton Quay. As 'Windy Wellington,' it's famous for its strong winds due to its location on the Cook Strait.
name: Wellington
address: New Zealand

excerpt: Distinctive, beehive-shaped 1960s designed building housing Prime Ministerial and cabinet offices.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Wellington, The Beehive stands as a striking testament to modern architecture and political history. This iconic building, designed by British architect Sir Basil Spence and constructed between 1964 and 1979, is renowned for its unique beehive shape that sparks both admiration and debate among locals and visitors alike. As the home of New Zealand's Prime Ministerial offices, it offers a fascinating glimpse into the workings of government.
name: Beehive
address: Ground Floor/1 Molesworth Street, Pipitea, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, affectionately known as Te Papa, is a treasure trove that beautifully encapsulates the essence of New Zealand. Nestled in Wellington, this national museum and art gallery offers an engaging journey through the country's diverse cultures, stunning landscapes, and unique wildlife. With its cutting-edge technology and interactive displays, visitors can immerse themselves in captivating stories from both past and present.
name: Museum Of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa
address: Customhouse Quay, Wellington Central, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Gothic revival cathedral built in the 1860s, with wooden arches, stained glass & guided tours.
detail_description: Old St Paul's is a Gothic revival cathedral constructed in the 1860s by the Anglican Church. It is renowned as one of New Zealand's greatest heritage sites and a prime example of timber Gothic architecture. Despite no longer being an active parish, it remains popular for weddings, funerals, and religious services. The cathedral survived demolition in the 1960s when a new St Paul's was built nearby.
name: Old St Paul's
address: 34 Mulgrave Street, Pipitea, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The Harbourside Market in Wellington is a must-visit on Sunday mornings. It's a family-friendly spot where you can enjoy the beautiful waterfront and let everyone pick their own breakfast while taking in the nearby playground. The market offers an array of fresh produce, food trucks, and live entertainment, catering to all tastes. Operating from 7:30 am to 1 pm in Winter and until 2 pm in Summer, it's the city's oldest and most beloved market.
name: Harbourside Market
address: Corner Barnett and, Cable Street, Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Hilltop museum highlighting the city's cablecar transport system with original grip cars & gear.
detail_description: The Cable Car Museum, located at the top of Wellington's famous cable car route in Kelburn, offers a captivating journey through the history of the city's beloved cable car system. Housed in the original cable car winding house, this hilltop museum showcases two original grip cars and the remarkable winding machinery that powered them up and down the hill. With exhibits spanning three floors, visitors can explore the development of Wellington's iconic transport system, featuring cable cars from different eras and original winding machinery.
name: Cable Car Museum
address: 1A Upland Road, Kelburn, Wellington 6012, New Zealand

excerpt: Built in 1858, the city's oldest original house is now a colonial museum with tours & a lush garden.
detail_description: Nairn Street Cottage, the oldest surviving original home in Wellington, was built in 1858 by architect William Wallis for his family. The cottage has been meticulously preserved with original 19th-century furniture and fixtures, offering a glimpse into New Zealand's pioneering era. Visitors can explore the colonial history of the Wallis family through guided tours that detail life in early Wellington. The property also features an organic heritage garden.
name: Nairn Street Cottage
address: 68 Nairn Street, Mount Cook, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The National Library of New Zealand, located in Wellington's city center, is a significant repository of the country's literary and historical treasures. It houses a diverse collection of artifacts, historic documents, books, maps, and paintings dating back over 100 years. The library is also home to He Tohu, an exhibition featuring three pivotal historical documents. Beyond its academic value, the library offers engaging displays and exhibitions that appeal to tourists and locals alike.
name: National Library of New Zealand
address: 70 Molesworth Street, Thorndon, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Edwardian, neo-classical building with a colonnaded facade, housing New Zealand's parliament.
detail_description: The New Zealand Parliament Buildings in downtown Wellington are a must-see for visitors interested in politics and architecture. The complex includes the neo-classical Parliament House and the unique Beehive, which houses the Executive Wing. Guided tours offer insight into New Zealand's parliamentary process and showcase artwork from the Parliamentary Collection. The square in front of the buildings features a statue of Richard John Seddon, one of New Zealand's most influential politicians.
name: New Zealand Parliament Buildings
address: 1 Molesworth Street, Pipitea, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Built in 1887, the childhood home of author Katherine Mansfield offers guided tours & a gift shop.
detail_description: Katherine Mansfield House & Garden, located in Wellington's Thorndon district, is the childhood home of renowned author Katherine Mansfield. Built in 1887, this grand townhouse offers guided tours that provide an immersive experience into 19th century colonial life and the history of the acclaimed writer. The house has been restored to its former glory and now serves as a popular tourist attraction, celebrating the legacy of Katherine Mansfield.
name: Katherine Mansfield House & Garden
address: 25 Tinakori Road, Thorndon, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Contemporary art is showcased at this free museum, which also offers a children's activity space.
detail_description: The Dowse Art Museum, located in Lower Hutt, New Zealand, is a must-visit for art enthusiasts. This free and family-friendly museum boasts over 2000 items, making it one of the country's largest public art collections. Renowned for its quality exhibitions by national and international contemporary artists, the museum challenges traditional notions of art. It is particularly known for showcasing craft and design, with past exhibitions featuring artists like Peter Robinson and Liu Jianhua.
name: The Dowse Art Museum and Dowse Square
address: 45 Laings Road, Hutt Central, Lower Hutt 5010, New Zealand

detail_description: Red Rocks, located just an hour's walk from Wellington's city center, offers a captivating blend of natural beauty and Maori history. The landscape, shaped by undersea volcanic eruptions over 200 years ago, boasts striking red rocks colored by iron oxides and steeped in Maori folklore. The Red Rocks Walkway provides a family-friendly 5.4km coastal trek along a flat 4WD track leading to the beach with its unique red rock formations and native fur seal colony.
name: Red Rocks - Seals
address: Ōwhiro Bay, Wellington 6023, New Zealand

excerpt: Native-forest preserve with many ancient trees, wildlife viewing & walking paths.
detail_description: Otari-Wilton's Bush is a captivating native-forest preserve in Wellington, New Zealand. It offers a mesmerizing experience with its ancient trees, diverse wildlife, and picturesque walking paths. The reserve boasts 1,200 stunning specimens from New Zealand and surrounding islands, including towering black beech trees, vibrant daisies, and blooming rata trees with rich red foliage.
name: Otari-Wilton's Bush
address: 150 Wilton Road, Wilton, Wellington 6012, New Zealand

detail_description: Courtenay Place is a lively area in the downtown district, perfect for people watching and soaking up the vibrant atmosphere. It's also close to Cuba Street, another great spot for strolling and taking in the local scene. Additionally, visitors can venture out to Miramar to visit the Weta Cave, which serves as a gateway to Weta Workshop and Studios. This renowned studio is famous for its contributions to iconic films like the Lord of the Rings trilogy.
name: Courtenay Place
address: Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Frank Kitts Park, located in the Wellington region of New Zealand, is a public park dedicated to the city's former mayor, Sir Francis Joseph Kitts. The park features an amphitheatre-style seating area and a playground with swings and a lighthouse. It also boasts an impressive collection of artworks including sculptures by Tanya Ashken, Paul Dibble, Charles Stone, and Len Lye.
name: Frank Kitts Park
address: Waterfront, Wellington Central, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The Garage Project Taproom: 91 Aro is a must-visit spot in New Zealand for beer enthusiasts. Situated near the brewery, this taproom offers an extensive selection of craft beers, showcasing the brewery's innovative and daring approach to brewing. From unconventional flavors to classic brews, there's something for every taste preference. The taproom also serves delectable bar snacks that pair perfectly with the beers.
name: Garage Project Aro Taproom: 91 Aro
address: 91 Aro Street, Aro Valley, Wellington 6021, New Zealand

detail_description: The Bucket Fountain in Wellington is a unique and iconic attraction located on Cuba Street. This quirky fountain, installed in 1969, features brightly colored buckets that fill with water and surprise passersby with unexpected splashes. Originally known as the Water Mobile, it was later renamed the Bucket Fountain. A popular landmark in the city, it adds a playful touch to the vibrant Cuba Mall area and has become an essential experience for visitors to Wellington.
name: Bucket Fountain
address: Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Pukeahu National War Memorial Park in Wellington, New Zealand is a solemn and significant site dedicated to honoring the country's soldiers who served and perished in major conflicts such as the South African War and both World Wars. The park features striking red sandstone columns leading to the Tomb of the Unknown Warrior and the impressive Carillon Tower with its bells commemorating various battles.
name: Pukeahu National War Memorial Park
address: State Highway 1, Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The Old Government Buildings, located on Whitmore Street in Wellington's CBD, is a historic site dating back to 1876. This majestic wooden structure, one of the world's largest, boasts Italian-inspired architecture and a lavishly decorated interior. It was initially lacking women's bathrooms for two decades after completion. The building is now part of the Government Buildings Historic Reserve and has been designated as a 'Category ' building by the New Zealand Historic Places Trust.
name: Old Government Buildings, Wellington
address: 55 Lambton Quay, Pipitea, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: The Embassy Theatre in Wellington is a grand and extravagant cinema that has become an iconic building for locals. It boasts one of the largest screens in the Southern Hemisphere and has a classical design that harks back to the 1920s era when it was built. The marble staircase, wooden features, and tiling all contribute to its timeless charm.
name: Embassy Theatre
address: 10 Kent Terrace, Mount Victoria, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Hiking to the 445-m. peak of this mountain provides views of the city, harbour & mountains.
detail_description: Mount Kaukau, standing at 445 meters above sea level, is the highest point in Wellington and offers breathtaking panoramic views of the city, harbor, and surrounding mountains. It's a popular recreational spot with various walking tracks suitable for all fitness levels. The Skyline Walkway leads to the summit where visitors can enjoy stunning vistas of Wellington, Hutt Valley, Porirua, and even the South Island. Additionally, it is home to Wellington's central television transmitter tower.
name: Mount Kaukau
address: Khandallah, Wellington 6035, New Zealand

detail_description: Scorching Bay, located in Karaka Bays on the Miramar peninsula at the entrance to Wellington harbor, offers a picturesque setting with clear aquamarine waters and verdant hills. The beach is ideal for a leisurely day of beach cricket and milkshakes from the nearby Scorch-O-Rama cafe. Visitors can enjoy golden sands, a grassy area, changing rooms, outdoor showers, and shelter from northerly winds.
name: Scorching Bay
address: Wellington Region, New Zealand

excerpt:
Lyall Bay is a bay and suburb on the south side of the Rongotai isthmus in Wellington, New Zealand.
The bay is a popular surf beach, featuring a breakwater at the eastern end. It is home to two surf lifesaving clubs and has also been the site of surf lifesaving championships. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Lyall Bay, located in Wellington, New Zealand, is a charming suburb and bay area known for its popular surf beach. The eastern end of the bay features a breakwater and is home to two surf lifesaving clubs as well as hosting surf lifesaving championships. Additionally, it's a favorite spot for early brunch at Spruce Goose and Maranui with an impeccable beach perfect for picnics and enjoying stunning sunsets.
name: Lyall Bay
address: Wellington 6022, New Zealand

excerpt: Memorial building to British settlers with history exhibits & interactive programs for children.
detail_description: The Petone Settlers Museum is a memorial building dedicated to British settlers, offering history exhibits and interactive programs for children. Located in the suburb of Petone, directly across the harbor from central Wellington, it showcases the stories of early settlers who first arrived in New Zealand. The museum features exhibits depicting Petone through different ages and includes a replica steerage cabin to provide insight into the experience of 1840 settlers.
name: Petone Settlers Museum
address: 130 Petone Settlers Museum, 160 The Esplanade, Petone, Lower Hutt 5012, New Zealand

excerpt: Small art space featuring portrait paintings by New Zealand artists in a diverse range of styles.
detail_description: The New Zealand Portrait Gallery is a small yet impactful art space located in a historic shed on the Wellington waterfront. It showcases diverse portrait paintings by New Zealand artists, featuring famous figures like politicians and actors as well as lesser-known individuals who have contributed significantly to New Zealand's narrative. The gallery's exhibitions cover a wide range of topics, from the portrayal of the New Zealand Wars in film to inventive takes on portraiture through various mediums such as painting, photography, and sculpture.
name: The New Zealand Portrait Gallery
address: Shed 11/60 Lady Elizabeth Lane, Pipitea, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Hiakai is a culinary gem in Wellington that beautifully celebrates Maori cuisine, offering an unforgettable experience for those looking to indulge in something truly special. This innovative restaurant, led by the talented Chef Monique Fiso, blends traditional Maori ingredients and cooking methods with contemporary flair. As the first Wahine-led establishment to earn three hats at the Cuisine Good Food Awards and named Chef of the Year in 2022, Hiakai has garnered significant recognition for its modern take on indigenous flavors.
name: HIAKAI
address: 40 Wallace Street, Mount Cook, Wellington 6021, New Zealand

detail_description: Pencarrow Upper Lighthouse, the first permanent lighthouse in New Zealand, offers a picturesque coastal walk or bike ride from Eastbourne. The track provides stunning views of Wellington Harbour, the city, the sea, and the South Island. The 1906 lighthouse stands at the storm-lashed entrance to Wellington Harbour and holds tales of early settlement and shipwrecks. Visitors can also access another lighthouse on a loop track and enjoy scenic vistas along the rugged coastline.
name: Pencarrow Upper Lighthouse
address: Pencarrow Head, Lower Hutt 5013, New Zealand

excerpt: Popular locale offering upscale, creative fish dishes & steaks in a relaxed & bustling atmosphere.
detail_description: Ortega Fish Shack is a stylish and cosmopolitan restaurant in New Zealand's capital city, offering upscale and creative fish dishes as well as steaks in a relaxed and bustling atmosphere. The menu focuses on seafood, featuring highlights such as lobster-and-prawn ravioli and sautéed paua with braised pork cheek in an Asian-style sauce. The beer list is diverse, featuring selections from Wellington makers and other excellent beers from around New Zealand and the world.
name: Ortega Fish Shack
address: 16 Majoribanks Street, Mount Victoria, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Wellington Harbour, located in New Zealand's capital city, offers a range of activities for visitors. From a purpose-built diving platform near Te Papa to an aerial obstacle course at Adrenalin Forest and scenic helicopter flights above the harbor, there's something for everyone.
name: Wellington Harbour
address: Wellington Region, New Zealand

detail_description: Carlucci Land in Wellington offers a unique blend of mini-golf and rustic sculptures created by artist Carl Gifford. The 18-hole mini-golf course features a cool junkyard theme, adding an interesting twist to the game. The venue showcases imaginative artworks made from recycled materials, creating a quirky and engaging atmosphere. Visitors can expect a mix of challenging and easier holes suitable for both adults and kids, all set amidst unconventional steam punk decor.
name: Carlucci Land
address: 281 Happy Valley Road, Ōwhiro Bay, Wellington 6023, New Zealand

detail_description: Mabel's is a must-visit eatery in the capital, offering deliciously authentic Burmese cuisine that celebrates its roots. The restaurant pays homage to co-owner Marlars' grandmother, Mabel, who opened one of the country's first Burmese restaurants almost 50 years ago. The warm and earthy interior design reflects Yangon's colonial-era architecture.
name: Mabel’s
address: 66 Tory Street, Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: Oriental Bay Beach is a popular destination in Wellington, known for its proximity to the city center and pristine promenade. Visitors can enjoy the soft sand and calm waters, making it an ideal spot for families. The beach offers beautiful views of the harbor and a nearby playground for kids. It's also a favorite after-work spot with a great view of the cityscape framed by Mount Kaukau.
name: Oriental Bay Beach
address: 166 Oriental Parade, Oriental Bay, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

excerpt: Urban recreation space offering a skateboard park, basketball courts, a playground & a cafe.
detail_description: Waitangi Park is a vibrant urban recreational space located in the heart of Wellington. It offers a variety of activities for visitors, including a skateboard park, basketball courts, and a playground for children. The park also features a cafe where visitors can relax and enjoy refreshments. With its lush green spaces, it's an ideal spot for families to let kids run around and play. The council has made significant improvements to the park, making it feel safer and more inviting for everyone.
name: Waitangi Park
address: Herd Street, Te Aro, Wellington 6011, New Zealand

detail_description: If you're seeking a relatively short and easy walk that takes around 2 hours to finish, the Mount Victoria Lookout Walkway is an excellent choice. This route is suitable for individuals with average fitness levels and encompasses three different walkways: Hataitai to City Walkway, Southern Walkway, and Newtown to Hataitai Walkway. The track offers a glimpse of Wellington's stunning Town Belt, which encircles the city with wooded hills. Covering a distance of 4.
name: Mount Victoria Lookout Walkway
address: Mount Victoria, Wellington 6011, New Zealand
